		content: "proprietary to Onepoint. We do not go out on the web, and the tool is designed to have proprietary data sources in it. So, having understood that data quality is the issue, the next question is, what specific aspects? So let's imagine we're struggling with the accuracy of data and also completeness of those first two so Shashin will go to the next level. You'll see at this point we also have the option if we wish to not only choose from the suggested options, but also put in free text for the purpose of today, we won't do that, but that is an option. You can go straight in if you're an expert IT user. So in this scenario, we're driving into the root causes of data quality, and we're going to say that we're only on manual checks. And the third one, Shashin, please. We're not actively involved in addressing these issues at the moment, because we've got resources, a common problem. So at this stage, you'll see the smiley face on the right has started to become a bit happier. It's not quite got to the point where it can produce the report, but it's getting there. So having understood the nature of the issue, we're now getting into what are the main challenges you face on manual checks and user feedbacks. So the manual checks are time-consuming. Yes, definitely the first one and the second one, and user feedbacks inconsistent. So what's happening here is the LLM tool is creating a unique question, and it's also populating the answers uniquely as well. This is not predetermined. This is not linear. This is totally emergent in its inquiry approach and in the data and content it's using. So now we're getting to how do we prioritize data quality issues? Well, the next well, we think we do prioritize, not based on business operations. That will be the first answer end users, because they tell them those two I think would be a good scenario. So we're getting into the last stage of the question in terms of, what do we do today to manage and improve data quality? So we're going to suggest, in this scenario, that we probably use spreadsheet number one, and I think we use number three. We use some scripts, but we're pretty limited on our technical skills. So at this point, you'll see that we're getting pretty much into the details, and the confidence indicator has now generated the fact that it's smiling, and we can actually generate a report. So at this point we will generate a report. So in literally less than I started at 10 past, in less than two to three minutes, we've gone from a very unknown understanding about the client's data issues and what they're doing to a very refined clarification on the issue. Some topics are out of scope, some are in and we've begun to understand what the clients themselves do with regards to actions. So what we now have is a high-level diagnostic report. So we have suggested courses of action which have been generated from the exercise. So guidance on a data quality management tool, prioritization framework and quality training. For example, those of you familiar with data management will recognize a lot of these actions. The report also then highlights what to avoid, which are critical risk issues, and also highlights the...\n" +
